[[Category:7th-century Japanese physicians]] [[Category:8th-century Japanese physicians]] [[Category:Japanese medical educators]] [[Category:7th-century Japanese medical educators]] [[Category:8th-century Japanese medical educators]] [[Category:Government offices of the RitsuryЕҚ system]] [[Category:Physicians]] [[Category:Bureau of Medicine]] [[Category:History of medicine in Japan]] [[Category:New pages]][[category:original pages]][[ja:еҢ»еҚҡеЈ«]]

'''I Hakase''' (еҢ»еҚҡеЈ«) was an official position under the {{ill|RitsuryЕҚ system|ja|еҫӢд»ӨеҲ¶}}, belonging to the {{ill|Bureau of Medicine|ja|е…ёи–¬еҜ®}} within the {{ill|Ministry of the Imperial Household (RitsuryЕҚ system)|ja|е®®еҶ…зңҒ (еҫӢд»ӨеҲ¶)}}.
== Overview ==
The term "I Hakase" first appears in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|ж—Ҙжң¬жӣёзҙҖ}} in entries for the 14th and 15th years of {{ill|Emperor Kinmei|ja|ж¬ҪжҳҺеӨ©зҡҮ}}. These references, however, pertain to doctors sent as tribute from {{ill|Baekje|ja|зҷҫжёҲ}} and are unrelated to Japan's own administrative system. By the 4th year of {{ill|Emperor Tenmu|ja|еӨ©жӯҰеӨ©зҡҮ}} ({{ill|675|ja|675е№ҙ}}), the term "Outer Pharmacy Bureau" (еӨ–и–¬еҜ®), later known as the Bureau of Medicine, is documented. It is inferred that the administrative structure equivalent to the Bureau of Medicine had already been established during the reigns of Emperor Tenmu and Empress JitЕҚ.
The position of I Hakase was held by a single appointee with an equivalent rank of {{ill|Junior Seventh Rank, Lower Grade|ja|жӯЈдёғдҪҚдёӢ}}, making it the highest-ranking post among the various specialists within the Bureau of Medicine. Among the ten physicians employed, one with superior knowledge and experience was selected as I Hakase. The primary duties involved teaching various {{ill|medical prescriptions|ja|и–¬ж–№}} (yakuhЕҚ) and {{ill|pulse diagnosis texts|ja|и„ҲзөҢ}} (myakugyЕҚ) to the medical practitioners (еҢ»з”ҹ). Until the establishment of the position of {{ill|Onna I Hakase|ja|еҘіеҢ»еҚҡеЈ«}}, the I Hakase was also responsible for orally teaching obstetrics to 30 female physicians recruited from among official maidservants. Both male and female physicians were required to undergo monthly examinations.
In addition to {{ill|official salary|ja|дҪҚзҰ„}} and {{ill|seasonal salary|ja|еӯЈзҰ„}}, the I Hakase received a one-time fee (жқҹи„©) of one piece of cloth from each entering medical student. According to a decree issued on February 18, {{ill|791|ja|е»¶жҡҰ10е№ҙ}}, the I Hakase was also granted four chЕҚ of {{ill|land allocated for official use|ja|иҒ·з”°}}.<ref>гҖҺ{{ill|Ruisan Sandai Kyaku|ja|йЎһиҒҡдёүд»Јж ј}}гҖҸ, Volume 15, "Provisions for Official Land, Rank Land, and Administrative Land."</ref>
