{{afc comment|1=I Hakase is too ambiguous in english so using Medical Hakase as the name[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 19:15, 27 March 2025 (UTC)}}
'''I Hakase''' (еҢ»еҚҡеЈ«) was an official position under the {{ill|RitsuryЕҚ system|ja|еҫӢд»ӨеҲ¶}}, belonging to the {{ill|Bureau of Pharmacy|ja|е…ёи–¬еҜ®|1=Bureau of Pharmacy|2=ja|3=е…ёи–¬еҜ®|4=fr|5=Bureau de pharmacie}} within the {{ill|Ministry of the Imperial Household (RitsuryЕҚ system)|ja|е®®еҶ…зңҒ (еҫӢд»ӨеҲ¶)}}.
== Overview ==
The term "I Hakase" first appears in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|ж—Ҙжң¬жӣёзҙҖ}} in entries for the 14th and 15th years of {{ill|Emperor Kinmei|ja|ж¬ҪжҳҺеӨ©зҡҮ}}. These references, however, pertain to doctors sent as tribute from {{ill|Baekje|ja|зҷҫжёҲ}} and are unrelated to Japan's own administrative system. By the 4th year of {{ill|Emperor Tenmu|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu}} ({{ill|675|ja|675th year}}), the term "Outer Pharmacy Bureau" (еӨ–и–¬еҜ®), later known as the Bureau of Medicine, is documented. It is inferred that the administrative structure equivalent to the Bureau of Medicine had already been established during the reigns of Emperor Tenmu and Empress JitЕҚ.
The position of I Hakase was held by a single appointee with an equivalent Rank of {{ill|Junior Seventh Rank|lt=Junior Seventh Rank, Lower Grade|ja|жӯЈдёғдҪҚдёӢ|1=Senior Seventh Rank|lt=Senior Seventh Rank, Lower Grade}}, making it the highest-Ranking post among the various specialists within the Bureau of Medicine. Among the ten physicians employed, one with superior knowledge and experience was selected as I Hakase. The primary duties involved teaching various {{ill|medical prescriptions|ja|и–¬ж–№}} (yakuhЕҚ) and {{ill|pulse diagnosis texts|ja|и„ҲзөҢ}} (myakugyЕҚ) to the medical practitioners (еҢ»з”ҹ). Until the establishment of the position of {{ill|Onna I Hakase|ja|еҘіеҢ»еҚҡеЈ«}}, the I Hakase was also responsible for orally teaching obstetrics to 30 female physicians recruited from among official maidservants. Both male and female physicians were required to undergo monthly examinations.
In addition to {{ill|official salary|ja|дҪҚзҰ„}} and {{ill|seasonal salary|ja|еӯЈзҰ„}}, the I Hakase received a one-time fee (жқҹи„©) of one piece of cloth from each entering medical student. According to a decree issued on February 18, {{ill|791|ja|е»¶жҡҰ10th year}}, the I Hakase was also granted four chЕҚ of {{ill|land allocated for official use|ja|иҒ·з”°}}.<ref>гҖҺ{{ill|Ruisan Sandai Kyaku|ja|йЎһиҒҡдёүд»Јж ј}}гҖҸ, Volume 15, "Provisions for Official Land, Rank Land, and Administrative Land."</ref>
